const Q_CRK_1997=[{"id": "objective>CRK>1997>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In extolling the sovereignty of God, Amos contrasted Him with the Nile which he described as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rising and sinking</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">drying and flooding</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the source of the waters of the sea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the source of Egypt's power</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Amos 8:8, Amos contrasted God with the Nile and rivers of Egypt when he says \"The whole land will rise like the Nile ...and then sink like the rivers of Egypt.\".</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">By keeping God's covenant, the people of Israel would become</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the conquerors of nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> a nation where God would manifest Himself</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the inheritors of the earth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a kingdom of priests of God</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Exodus 19:5-6, God makes a covenant with the Israelites. He promises that if they obey His voice and keep His covenant, they would be His treasured possession among all peoples, and they would be a kingdom of priests and a holy nation. Therefore, by keeping God's covenant, the people of Israel would become a kingdom of priests of God.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Jeremiah, the vital element in the new covenant God would make the Jews was that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> He would bless all nations through the Jews</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man would be enabled to keep God's law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">salvation would come through a virgin's seed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the individual would be accountable before God</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Jeremiah, the prophet speaks of a new covenant that God would make with the Jews. The vital element in this new covenant was that man would be enabled to keep God's law. This is because the new covenant would involve God writing His laws in the hearts of the people, thus enabling them to keep His laws. This is different from the old covenant where the laws were written on tablets of stone and people found it difficult to keep them.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : THE NEW COVENANT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joseph saw his rise to leadership position in Egypt in relation to his brothers as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a proof of his superiority over them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an opportunity to avenge their evil deeds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a time to test their honesty</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a means of preserving their lives</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joseph saw his rise to leadership position in Egypt in relation to his brothers as a means of preserving their lives. This is evident in Genesis 45:5-7 where Joseph reveals his identity to his brothers and tells them not to be distressed or angry with themselves because God sent him ahead of them to preserve life. He saw his position as part of God's plan to ensure the survival of his family during the severe famine.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JOSEPH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''If you will go with me, I will go'; but if you will not go with me, I will not go''. In the statement above, 'you' refers to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Balaam</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Deborah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jael</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement 'If you will go with me, I will go; but if you will not go with me, I will not go' was made by Barak to Deborah in the Bible (Judges 4:8). Therefore, 'you' in the statement refers to Deborah.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JUDGES - DEBORAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The name Ichabod means</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">without glory</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unfolding glory</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perpetual glory</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">departed glory</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> It was a name given by the wife of Phinehas, the son of Eli, when she heard that the Ark of God had been captured by the Philistines and that her husband and father-in-law were dead (1 Samuel 4:21).</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : CONDITION OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How did David perceive that his child from Bathsheba was dead?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bathsheba lamented the loss of her child</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he saw his servants whispering together</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he received a message to that effect from Joab</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God revealed it to him through Nathan</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David noticed that his servants were whispering among themselves so he perceived that the child was dead.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFTER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''As one falls before the wicked you have fallen'' This is a part of David's lamentation over</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Absalom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jonathan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abner</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase ''As one falls before the wicked you have fallen'' is a part of David's lamentation over Abner. This can be found in 2 Samuel 3:34 where David laments over the death of Abner, who was killed by Joab. David considered Abner's death as a great loss and mourned for him.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFTER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The mother of the living child asked Solomon to give the child to the other woman because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">killing the child would serve no useful purpose</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">her heart yearned for the child</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">she was confident that the king would ensure justice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">she believed the child would recognize her at maturity</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the biblical story, the real mother of the living child asked King Solomon to give the child to the other woman because she would rather see her child alive and in the care of another woman than see her child killed. This was a test set by King Solomon to determine the real mother, as the real mother's love would not allow harm to come to her child. Therefore, the correct answer is 'killing the child would serve no useful purpose'.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : THE WISDOM OF SOLOMON"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea's matrimonial experience symbolizes God's intention to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reform Israel and make her greater</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">review His covenant with Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discipline Israel for her infidelity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">redeem Israel from her unfaithfulness</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea's marriage to Gomer, a prostitute, was a symbolic act commanded by God to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to Him. Despite Gomer's repeated infidelity, Hosea was commanded to take her back, symbolizing God's enduring love and willingness to forgive Israel despite her unfaithfulness. Therefore, the correct answer is 'redeem Israel from her unfaithfulness'.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The harlotry of Gomer is compared to Israel's</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abandonment of the ephod</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">false and insincere sacrifices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oppression of the poor</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unfaithfulness to God</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The harlotry of Gomer is compared to Israel's unfaithfulness to God. In the book of Hosea, Gomer, the wife of Hosea, is used as a metaphor for the unfaithfulness of the Israelites to God. Just as Gomer was unfaithful to her husband, so were the Israelites unfaithful to God by worshipping other gods and breaking the covenant they had with Him.</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''Holy, holy, holy is the Lord of hosts; the whole earth is full of his glory'', This statement was made in the year</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Solomon dedicated the temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Josiah completed his reformation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Uzziah of Judah died</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David brought the ark to Jerusalem</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement 'Holy, holy, holy is the Lord of hosts; the whole earth is full of his glory' was made in the year Uzziah of Judah died. This statement is found in Isaiah 6:3. The context of this chapter is the vision that Isaiah had of the Lord in the year that King Uzziah died. In this vision, seraphim were praising God with these words.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''Hear the word of the LORD, you rulers of Sodom! Give ear to the teaching of our God, you people of Gomorrah!''The nation referred to as Sodom and Gomorrah in the statement above is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Judah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samaria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ephraim</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Isaiah 1:10, the prophet Isaiah uses the names Sodom and Gomorrah metaphorically to refer to the nation of Israel. He does this to express God's displeasure with Israel's sins and their disobedience to His laws. Sodom and Gomorrah were cities known for their wickedness and were destroyed by God as a result. By comparing Israel to these cities, Isaiah was highlighting the severity of Israel's sins.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF JEREMIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah was not anxious to accept God's call to become a prophet because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it was a hazardous profession</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he knew that the people would not listen to him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he needed to know God more</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he was too young and inexperienced</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He felt that he was too young/was inexperienced as a prophet. He did not have the message to the people. He did not know how to speak/not a good speaker. The task was too difficult overwhelming for him.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF JEREMIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The devil's principal purpose for tempting Jesus Christ was to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">show that nobody is above temptation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demonstrate that he controls the world</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lure Jesus Christ from His mission</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prove that afterall, Jesus is only human</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This is the correct answer. It shows nobody is above temptation.</div>", "topic": "THE BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATIONS OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''Foxes have holes, and birds of the air have nests; but the Son of man has nowhere to lay his head,'' This statement above implies that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discipleship costs much</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Son of man needs no house</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suffering is inevitable in life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">church buildings are unnecessary</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement ''Foxes have holes, and birds of the air have nests; but the Son of man has nowhere to lay his head,'' implies that discipleship costs much. Jesus was explaining to a would-be follower that following Him might mean giving up physical comforts and securities. This is a cost that one must be willing to pay to be a disciple of Jesus.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Luke, following Jesus involves</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">confession</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">self-denial</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">baptism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">daily prayers</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of Luke, following Jesus involves self-denial. This is based on Luke 9:23 where Jesus says, 'If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross daily and follow me.' Self-denial in this context means giving up one's own desires or interests for the sake of others or for a higher purpose.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the healing ministry of Jesus Christ which of the following played a very vital role?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">repentance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">love</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">patience</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the healing ministry of Jesus Christ, faith played a very vital role. Many instances in the Bible, particularly in the Gospels, show that Jesus often healed people based on their faith. For example, in Matthew 9:22, Jesus heals a woman who had been suffering from a bleeding disorder for twelve years, saying 'your faith has made you well.' Therefore, faith is the correct answer.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus healed the only son of the widow of Nain because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the crowd pleaded with Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the widow demonstrated faith in Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He had compassion on her</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He wanted to make people believe in Him</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, Luke 7:11-17, Jesus healed the only son of the widow of Nain out of compassion. When Jesus saw the widow, his heart went out to her and he said, 'Don't cry.' Then he went up and touched the bier they were carrying him on, and the bearers stood still. He said, 'Young man, I say to you, get up!' The dead man sat up and began to talk, and Jesus gave him back to his mother.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The healing of the paralytic brought by his four friends demonstrates</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> the power of Jesus to heal all types of diseases</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that the friends had faith in the healing power of Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the compassion of Jesus on the sick man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that Jesus has power to forgive sin</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, Mark 2:1-12, the healing of the paralytic brought by his four friends demonstrates that Jesus has power to forgive sin. When Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralyzed man, 'Son, your sins are forgiven.' Some teachers of the law were sitting there, thinking to themselves, 'Why does this fellow talk like that? He's blaspheming! Who can forgive sins but God alone?' Immediately Jesus knew in his spirit that this was what they were thinking in their hearts, and he said to them, 'Why are you thinking these things? Which is easier: to say to this paralyzed man, 'Your sins are forgiven,' or to say, 'Get up, take your mat and walk'? But I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins.' So he said to the man, 'I tell you, get up, take your mat and go home.' He got up, took his mat and walked out in full view of them all. This amazed everyone and they praised God, saying, 'We have never seen anything like this!'</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Mark and Luke, the response of blind Bartimaeus to his healing was to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">follow Jesus immediately</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">run to show himself to the priests</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">confess Jesus as a prophet</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">speak to the Jews about Jesus</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of Mark (10:52) and Luke (18:43), after Jesus healed blind Bartimaeus, he followed Jesus immediately. This shows his gratitude and faith in Jesus.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE RESURRECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable which teaches about God's judgement is that of the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sower</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lost sheep</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">weeds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mustard seed</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the weeds (also known as the parable of the tares) found in Matthew 13:24-30, teaches about God's judgement. In this parable, Jesus explains that at the end of the age, God will separate the 'weeds' (evil doers) from the 'wheat' (righteous), which is a metaphor for the final judgement.</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES ABOUT LOVE FOR ONE ANOTHER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the good Samaritan Implies that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samaritans always love their neighbours</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> priests and Levites hardly show love</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">neighbourliness is expressed in love and concern</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a good neighbour must show love to his enemies</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the good Samaritan is a story told by Jesus in the Bible, found in Luke 10:25–37. It is about a traveler who is stripped of clothing, beaten, and left half dead alongside the road. A priest and a Levite pass by, but a Samaritan stops to help him. The story is a lesson about compassion and love towards all individuals, regardless of their race or religion. Therefore, the correct answer is that 'neighbourliness is expressed in love and concern'.</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES ABOUT LOVE OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Luke ends the Sermon on the Plain with an analogy of a building to emphasize the importance of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">preaching and hearing the word</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hearing and obeying the word</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">studying and doing the word</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">preaching and abiding by the word</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The analogy of a building at the end of the Sermon on the Plain in Luke 6:46-49 is used by Jesus to emphasize the importance of not just hearing His words, but also acting on them. He compares the person who comes to Him, hears His words, and acts on them to a man building a house, who dug deep and laid the foundation on rock. When a flood arose, the river burst against that house but could not shake it, because it had been well built. Therefore, the correct answer is 'hearing and obeying the word'.</div>", "topic": "SERMON ON THE MOUNT : THE TEACHINGS ON THE MOUNT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus implies in His teaching on adultery, prayer, alms and and fasting that these are more of matters of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the heart</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">individual interpretation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">religious beliefs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">social norms</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In His teachings on adultery, prayer, alms, and fasting, Jesus emphasizes the importance of the heart's condition. He teaches that these are not just external actions, but internal matters of the heart. For instance, in the case of adultery, He says that even looking at a woman lustfully is equivalent to committing adultery in one's heart. Similarly, prayer, alms, and fasting are not to be done for show, but with a sincere heart.</div>", "topic": "SERMON ON THE MOUNT : THE DEMANDS OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus injunction not to lay up treasures on earth for ourselves implies that the christian should</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not bank his money</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">give his money to charity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not be extravagant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be rich in good works</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus' teaching about not laying up treasures on earth implies that Christians should focus on being 'rich in good works'. This means that instead of focusing on accumulating earthly wealth, Christians should focus on doing good works that have eternal value. This is because earthly treasures are temporary and can be destroyed or stolen, but treasures in heaven are eternal and cannot be destroyed or stolen.</div>", "topic": "SERMON ON THE MOUNT : THE DEMANDS OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The seventy disciples who returned from their missionary work were told by Jesus to rejoice because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were well received by people</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the spirits were subject to them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their names were written in heaven</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they preached to many people</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Then at the right moment Jesus said, \"Rejoice that your names are recorded in heaven!\" Jesus' comment reveals what scripture has already recorded. </div>", "topic": "MISSION OF THE DISCIPLES : THE MISSION OF THE SEVENTY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Matthew, Jesus entered Jerusalem riding</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a horse and a donkey</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an ass and a horse</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a colt and a donkey</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an ass and a colt</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of Matthew, specifically Matthew 21:1-7, Jesus entered Jerusalem riding on an ass and a colt. This fulfilled a prophecy from Zechariah 9:9 that the Messiah would enter Jerusalem in this manner. The ass and the colt are the same animal, the colt is a young, untrained ass. The other options are incorrect because they mention a horse, which is not mentioned in the biblical account.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The prayer of Jesus before His arrest showed that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was sorrowful and troubled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His disciples had not understood Him thoroughly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was not prepared to die on the cross</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He wanted His disciples to be prayerful</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Matthew 26:38, Jesus expressed his sorrow and trouble before his arrest, saying 'My soul is overwhelmed with sorrow to the point of death.' This shows that he was indeed sorrowful and troubled.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : THE TRIALS OF JESUS BEFORE THE HIGH PRIEST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''Are you the king of the Jews?'' Jesus reply to the question above by Pilate was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">You have said so''</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">My kingship is not of this word''</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''Who has made you a prince and a judge over us?''</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> ''Why put me to the test, you hypocrites?''</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In John 18:37, Jesus answered Pilate's question by saying, 'You have said so.' </div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : THE TRIALS OF JESUS BEFORE PILATE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Matthew, when the woman went to see the sepulchre, they</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">saw an angel sitting upon the stone</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">met Jesus on the way</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">found that the disciples had been there</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">found the guards rolling back the stone</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of Matthew, specifically Matthew 28:2, when the women went to see the sepulchre, they saw an angel of the Lord descending from heaven, coming and rolling back the stone and sitting upon it. The angel's appearance was like lightning, and his clothing was white as snow. The guards were so afraid of him that they shook and became like dead men.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus used the illustration of the vine to teach that a christian that abides in Him will surely</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be a good shepherd</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resurrect on the Last Day</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be a bread of life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bear much fruit</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In John 15:5, Jesus used the illustration of the vine to teach about the relationship between Him and His followers. He said, 'I am the vine, you are the branches. He who abides in Me, and I in him, bears much fruit; for without Me you can do nothing.' This means that a Christian who remains in Jesus, and in whom Jesus remains, will bear much fruit, symbolizing the good works and virtues that should characterize a Christian's life.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE TRUE VINE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Two of the seven disciples chosen to serve tables in the early church were</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Parmenas and Timon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Matthias and Cornelius</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nathaniel and Philip</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Stephen and Andrew</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They chose Stephen, a man full of faith and of the Holy Spirit, Philip, Prochorus, Nicanor, Timon, Parmenas, and Nicolaus, a proselyte of Antioch. The congregation presented these men to the apostles. When the apostles had prayed, they laid their hands on the chosen men.\" (Acts 6:5-6).</div>", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH : COMMUNAL LIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''Give me also this power, that any one whom I lay my hands may receive the Holy Spirit''. Peter rebuked the speaker for being</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">very crafty</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">money conscious</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ignorant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fraudulent</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The quote is from Acts 8:18-20, where Simon the sorcerer, seeing that the Holy Spirit was given through the laying on of the apostles' hands, offered them money to buy this power. Peter rebuked him for thinking that the gift of God could be purchased with money, indicating that Simon was money conscious.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COMMISSIONING AND MISSION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At the Beautiful Gate,Peter and John healed a man who was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lame</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">blind</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deaf</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dumb</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">True enough, it was what happened when Peter and John healed the lame man. According to Acts 3:9 (ESV), \"all the people saw him walking and praising God.\" They \"recognized him as the one who sat at the Beautiful Gate of the temple, asking for alms.\"</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The people referred to as pillars of the Jerusalem church, who gave Barnabas and Paul the right hand of fellowship were</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cephas, John and Mark</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">James, John and Silas</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">John, Silas and Simon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">James, Cephas and John</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Galatians 2:9 <br/> James, Cephas and John, those esteemed as pillars, gave me and Barnabas the right hand of fellowship when they recognized the grace given to me. </div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COUNCIL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The condition for justification according to Paul is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">merit and favour</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">possession of spiritual gifts</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ability to keep God's commandments</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith in Christ crucfied</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Apostle Paul in the New Testament, the condition for justification is faith in Christ crucified. Justification is a theological concept that means being declared righteous by God. Paul emphasizes that this is achieved not through human efforts or adherence to the law, but through faith in Jesus Christ and his sacrificial death on the cross.</div>", "topic": "JUSTIFICATION BY FAITH : MEANING AND BASIC CONDITIONS FOR JUSTIFICATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">On which of the following grounds will faith be null and promise void?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith is a necessary condition for justification</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">believers are saved through grace</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">salvation comes through adherence to the law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">justification is by God's grace</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul, faith would be null and promise void if salvation comes through adherence to the law. This is because Paul taught that salvation is by grace through faith in Jesus Christ, not by adherence to the law. If salvation could be achieved through the law, then faith in Christ would be unnecessary and the promise of salvation through faith would be void.</div>", "topic": "JUSTIFICATION BY FAITH : MEANING AND BASIC CONDITIONS FOR JUSTIFICATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Letter of Paul to the Romans, Christians are to yield themselves to God as men who</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have been raised from death to life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> no longer live by the works of law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive baptism after circumcision</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have listened to the gospel of Christ</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Letter of Paul to the Romans, specifically in Romans 6:13, Paul urges Christians to yield themselves to God as those who have been raised from death to life. This is a metaphorical way of saying that Christians, through faith and baptism, have died to their old sinful selves and have been raised to a new life in Christ. This concept is often referred to as 'spiritual resurrection' or 'regeneration'.</div>", "topic": "NEW LIFE IN CHRIST : CONDITIONS AND BENEFITS OF NEW LIFE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God sent His Son , Jesus Christ, into the world in the likeness of sinful flesh in order</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to destroy the law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> that the law might be fulfilled</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that man may walk in the flesh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to save the righteous</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Romans 8:3-4, God sent His Son, Jesus Christ, in the likeness of sinful flesh so that the righteous requirement of the law might be fulfilled in us. This means that Jesus, by living a sinless life and dying on the cross, fulfilled the law's requirement for perfect righteousness. This righteousness is then imputed to those who trust in Christ for their salvation. This is a key concept in Christian theology known as 'justification by faith'.</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">''......at the name of Jesus every knee should bow ....every tongues confess that Jesus Christ is Lord .....'' The statement above demonstrates the Lordship of Jesus over</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all religious persons</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all creation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">christians only</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">non christians only</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement is a quote from Philippians 2:10-11 in the Bible. It emphasizes the universal lordship of Jesus Christ over all creation, not just over religious persons, Christians, or non-Christians. Therefore, the correct answer is 'all creation'.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE RESURRECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul told the Corinthians that if any one has caused pain to the church he should be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">removed from their midst</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">punished severely</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forgiven and comforted</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">made to confess his sins</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">But if any one has caused pain, he has caused it not to me, but in some measure --not to put it too severely -- to you all. [6] For such a one this punishment by the majority is enough; [7] so you should rather turn to forgive and comfort him, or he may be overwhelmed by excessive sorrow.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The greatest spiritual gift to seek for is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">speaking in tongues</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">love</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">healing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> working of miracles</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in 1 Corinthians 13:13, Apostle Paul states that 'And now these three remain: faith, hope and love. But the greatest of these is love.' This implies that love is the greatest spiritual gift to seek for.</div>", "topic": "SPIRITUAL GIFTS : THE DIFFERENT SPIRITUAL GIFTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the civic responsibilities Christians are commanded to carry out is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">honouring elders in the society</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">maintaining holiness in life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obedience to lawful authority</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">observing the law faithfully</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Romans 13:1-2 in the Bible instructs Christians to be obedient to lawful authority. It states 'Let everyone be subject to the governing authorities, for there is no authority except that which God has established. The authorities that exist have been established by God. Consequently, whoever rebels against the authority is rebelling against what God has instituted, and those who do so will bring judgment on themselves.' This implies that one of the civic responsibilities Christians are commanded to carry out is obedience to lawful authority.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE NEED FOR OBEDIENCE TO AUTHORITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the course of his ministry, Paul worked night and day so that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he might not be a burden to any one</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his followers might eat</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he could raise money for the work of the gospel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he could pay the debt he was owing the brethren</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Surely you remember, brothers and sisters, our toil and hardship; we worked night and day in order not to be a burden to anyone while we preached the gospel of God to you.</div>", "topic": "DIGNITY OF LABOUR : BENEFITS OF DIGNITY OF LABOUR"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Those who have fallen asleep before the coming of the Lord are those</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sleeping naturally</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dead physically</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dead spiritually</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">who are unfaithful</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Therefore, those who are \"asleep\" in 1Thess 4 are those Christians who have died. By the context, we see Paul was referring to believers who die prior to Christ's coming for the Church at the Rapture.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : PREPARATION FOR HIS COMING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">James enjoins Christians to remain impartial by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">showing love to all without distinction</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loving their neighbours as themselves</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">treating all brethren equally</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">giving everyone his due</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James, Christians are encouraged to show impartiality by showing love to all without distinction. This is based on the principle of the 'royal law' as stated in James 2:8, which is to love your neighbor as yourself. However, the emphasis in James is on showing love without distinction, which means not showing favoritism or bias, and treating everyone with the same love and respect, regardless of their status or background.</div>", "topic": "IMPARTIALITY : CONCEPT OF IMPARTIALITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to James, the man who prays to God and at the same time doubts is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ignorant of God's purpose</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disobedient to God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">double-minded</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deceived by Satan</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">But let him ask in faith, with no doubting, for the one who doubts is like a wave of the sea that is driven and tossed by the wind.</div>", "topic": "EFFECTIVE PRAYER : THE REQUIREMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRAYER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter admonishes Christians that suffering for Christ's sake brings God's</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">salvation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">blessing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">love</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, Peter encourages Christians to endure suffering for Christ's sake, stating that it brings blessings from God. This is based on the belief that suffering for the sake of Christ is a form of sacrifice that God rewards with blessings.</div>", "topic": "INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS : CHRISTIAN ATTITUDE TO PERSECUTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>1997>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Matthew, Jesus entered Jerusalem riding</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a horse and a donkey</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> an ass and a horse</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a colt and a donkey</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an ass and a colt</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of Matthew (Matthew 21:1-11), Jesus entered Jerusalem riding on an ass and a colt. This fulfilled a prophecy from the Old Testament (Zechariah 9:9) and symbolized Jesus' humility and peace.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}];
